    {
      "id": "4uNIw2_C6TZAZP5eM6G1i",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 468.745221170249,
      "y": 564.746387228624,
      "width": 895.87939453125,
      "height": 675,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "aP",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1051373614,
      "version": 2061,
      "versionNonce": 1902233330,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1777999536878,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Requirement Analysis\n\nFunctional Requirements [Functionality of the system]:\n1.  Create a short url from a long url.\n      - Optinally support custom alias by users.\n      - Optinally support an expiration time.\n2.  be redirected to the original url from the short url.\n\nNon-Functional Requirements [Qualities of the system]: \n1.  Latency - Redirections should be low latency.  (~ 200 ms)\n2. Scale of the system - 100 millions daily active users + 1 billion urls. \n3. Uniquness of the shortcodes -> No collosions in the redirection logic.\n4. CAP theorm - High Availability with Evenutal Consisitency.\n    - In a distributed system, there is always gonna be Partition tolerance,\n      Like the databases we have, they would be horizontally scaled.\n    - Decision here is Should we chooise Strong Consistency or High Availability ?\n    - Do i need strong read after write consistency  i.e does every read of the system\n      have to read the latest write or else the system breaks \n      eg: banking appliation [trading money] or ticket booking [conflict booking same seat].\n    - Strong Consistency in URL shortern ?\n      -> Can be a No, because user takes some time to use the shortern url.\n      -> Also it can be handled, like we can re-direct it to the original node or show message\n          to user that we are still saving the url.\n      !!! Strong Consistency is good in this case but not mandatory !!\n   \n        \n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Requirement Analysis\n\nFunctional Requirements [Functionality of the system]:\n1.  Create a short url from a long url.\n      - Optinally support custom alias by users.\n      - Optinally support an expiration time.\n2.  be redirected to the original url from the short url.\n\nNon-Functional Requirements [Qualities of the system]: \n1.  Latency - Redirections should be low latency.  (~ 200 ms)\n2. Scale of the system - 100 millions daily active users + 1 billion urls. \n3. Uniquness of the shortcodes -> No collosions in the redirection logic.\n4. CAP theorm - High Availability with Evenutal Consisitency.\n    - In a distributed system, there is always gonna be Partition tolerance,\n      Like the databases we have, they would be horizontally scaled.\n    - Decision here is Should we chooise Strong Consistency or High Availability ?\n    - Do i need strong read after write consistency  i.e does every read of the system\n      have to read the latest write or else the system breaks \n      eg: banking appliation [trading money] or ticket booking [conflict booking same seat].\n    - Strong Consistency in URL shortern ?\n      -> Can be a No, because user takes some time to use the shortern url.\n      -> Also it can be handled, like we can re-direct it to the original node or show message\n          to user that we are still saving the url.\n      !!! Strong Consistency is good in this case but not mandatory !!\n   \n        \n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "KDcGihdnVyiKzUlfehtuz",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1591.4423124228108,
      "y": 570.1669782987976,
      "width": 146.63986206054688,
      "height": 125,
      "angle": 0,
