      "updated": 1778322005330,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "redirect(shortURL)\n- Returns a 302 redirect\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "center",
      "verticalAlign": "middle",
      "containerId": "1yTj_93f_gVbm_PJi48UY",
      "originalText": "redirect(shortURL)\n- Returns a 302 redirect\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "WwuztPFvW-xKHkxevdFXo",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 305.63855521468486,
      "y": 1928.0132716298556,
      "width": 477.4997253417969,
      "height": 500,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "at",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1517477554,
      "version": 823,
      "versionNonce": 719763630,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1778322016227,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Options for Redirection ?\n1. 302 Redirect:\n    -> A Temporary Redirect. \n    Browsers won't cache it, so it needs our \n    service every single time.\n    -> Good for Analystic in server and make \n    sure that the server works, as it hots server\n    everytime.\n\nSince we dont care about Analystics,\n302 makes more sense here...\n\n2. 301 Redirect:\n    -> A Permanent Redirect. Browser \n    knows where to redirect, and it won't\n    need our service anymore.\n    -> Good, if want to save the overhead\n    compute of lookingup the long url for \n    the short one.\n    -> Efficient but one-time use-case only !",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Options for Redirection ?\n1. 302 Redirect:\n    -> A Temporary Redirect. \n    Browsers won't cache it, so it needs our \n    service every single time.\n    -> Good for Analystic in server and make \n    sure that the server works, as it hots server\n    everytime.\n\nSince we dont care about Analystics,\n302 makes more sense here...\n\n2. 301 Redirect:\n    -> A Permanent Redirect. Browser \n    knows where to redirect, and it won't\n    need our service anymore.\n    -> Good, if want to save the overhead\n    compute of lookingup the long url for \n    the short one.\n    -> Efficient but one-time use-case only !",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "RSvKFmVJ36D2UseZ04rBJ",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 878.6505316319171,
      "y": 1917.1292575077675,
      "width": 1127.0391845703125,
      "height": 1625,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "au",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 207755698,
      "version": 3815,
      "versionNonce": 1120865650,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1778322045211,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "We want the short url to be:\n   1. fast\n   2. unique\n   3. short (5-7 chars max)\n\nPossible Options:\n\n1. Save Prefix of the long url\n    - So any long url, you chop off first few characters.\n      save the rest.\n    - Easy, fast but hardly any reliable.\n   Problem:\n    - Multiple urls can have the same prefix. So a single\n      prefix text can map to millions of other urls.\n\n   !!! Terriable Idea ! Don;t do this !!!\n\n2. Random Number Generator\n    - idea is, We can use random numbers to map the long urls.\n    - Problem is how big this random number should be to avoid\n      colloisions ?\n        -  Need Handle 1B urls -> random number between 1 to 1B atleast.\n           i.e 10^9 or 10 characters  >> our limit of 5-7 chars for short url.\n    - solution:\n      take big number -> use base64 encoding, 0-9, A-Z, a-z.  --> length will be 6.\n      eg: a code of len 6, then 62^6 ~= 56B, so random number between this range.\n      NOTE: 62 because, baseEncoding can have 62 possible chars it can use over 6 spaces each \n                -> Permutation: 62^6 \n    - Collision chances:\n      Interestingly, the chances of collisions are pretty high [ Birthday Praradox ]\n     \n      Birthday Paradox: \n        There is actually a 50% chance that 2 people having the same birthday \n        out of 23 people in the room even if there are 365 days in a year ! [ ** WOW **]\n\n      Interesting Stats:\n        Out of 1B randomly generated number, there are a chances of 880k colloisions.\n\n   Solution for the colloision:\n       - Check for the collision first, i.e once you genrate a random number, reduce to base64,\n         check in the database if it's exists ?\n        Only if it doesn't exist --> Save it ---> else run the logic again !\n \n3. Hash the long url:\n    - Most common approach !\n    - Take the long url, use a hash algorithm like SHA256, md5 etc -> hash -> base64 encode -> slice it for 6 chars.\n    - hash functions have waterfall effects:\n       If we even change 1 bit in the input, the whole hash fucntion will change. \n        -> This will Increase in the randomness [ This is good, less collision ] \n    - same as above for rest of the case.\n\n4. use a Counter:\n    - incrementing a counter for each new long url that comes in. -> base64 [for compactness].\n    - This guarntee there is never a collision. Also no need to do a extra read from DB for collision avoidance.\n    -  Problem:\n       Predictibility: Bad for security !!\n           Anyonc can extract our informations just my incrementing 1 by 1 the counter in short url.\n       Solution:\n            1. We can show warnings  for users, DONT short private/personal Urls.\n            2. Implement rate limiting, stop anyone to continuously scrap the site.\n    - Solution to this Predicitbility:\n        use Bijective function - These functions just issue a 1 to 1 mapping i.e it takes a number\n        and returns a hash [looks like base64 encoded], it creates 1 to 1 mapping in some ways.\n        Prevents the hacker to scrap by simply incrementing the counter.\n        eg: sqids.org [ Opensource library ]   ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "We want the short url to be:\n   1. fast\n   2. unique\n   3. short (5-7 chars max)\n\nPossible Options:\n\n1. Save Prefix of the long url\n    - So any long url, you chop off first few characters.\n      save the rest.\n    - Easy, fast but hardly any reliable.\n   Problem:\n    - Multiple urls can have the same prefix. So a single\n      prefix text can map to millions of other urls.\n\n   !!! Terriable Idea ! Don;t do this !!!\n\n2. Random Number Generator\n    - idea is, We can use random numbers to map the long urls.\n    - Problem is how big this random number should be to avoid\n      colloisions ?\n        -  Need Handle 1B urls -> random number between 1 to 1B atleast.\n           i.e 10^9 or 10 characters  >> our limit of 5-7 chars for short url.\n    - solution:\n      take big number -> use base64 encoding, 0-9, A-Z, a-z.  --> length will be 6.\n      eg: a code of len 6, then 62^6 ~= 56B, so random number between this range.\n      NOTE: 62 because, baseEncoding can have 62 possible chars it can use over 6 spaces each \n                -> Permutation: 62^6 \n    - Collision chances:\n      Interestingly, the chances of collisions are pretty high [ Birthday Praradox ]\n     \n      Birthday Paradox: \n        There is actually a 50% chance that 2 people having the same birthday \n        out of 23 people in the room even if there are 365 days in a year ! [ ** WOW **]\n\n      Interesting Stats:\n        Out of 1B randomly generated number, there are a chances of 880k colloisions.\n\n   Solution for the colloision:\n       - Check for the collision first, i.e once you genrate a random number, reduce to base64,\n         check in the database if it's exists ?\n        Only if it doesn't exist --> Save it ---> else run the logic again !\n \n3. Hash the long url:\n    - Most common approach !\n    - Take the long url, use a hash algorithm like SHA256, md5 etc -> hash -> base64 encode -> slice it for 6 chars.\n    - hash functions have waterfall effects:\n       If we even change 1 bit in the input, the whole hash fucntion will change. \n        -> This will Increase in the randomness [ This is good, less collision ] \n    - same as above for rest of the case.\n\n4. use a Counter:\n    - incrementing a counter for each new long url that comes in. -> base64 [for compactness].\n    - This guarntee there is never a collision. Also no need to do a extra read from DB for collision avoidance.\n    -  Problem:\n       Predictibility: Bad for security !!\n           Anyonc can extract our informations just my incrementing 1 by 1 the counter in short url.\n       Solution:\n            1. We can show warnings  for users, DONT short private/personal Urls.\n            2. Implement rate limiting, stop anyone to continuously scrap the site.\n    - Solution to this Predicitbility:\n        use Bijective function - These functions just issue a 1 to 1 mapping i.e it takes a number\n        and returns a hash [looks like base64 encoded], it creates 1 to 1 mapping in some ways.\n        Prevents the hacker to scrap by simply incrementing the counter.\n        eg: sqids.org [ Opensource library ]   ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
