    },
    {
      "id": "zqhvjE68cFX2XaBbW9BIN",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2450.2651221649126,
      "y": 1269.6234252559323,
      "width": 1165.1192626953125,
      "height": 675,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "ax",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 256737330,
      "version": 2002,
      "versionNonce": 1771249902,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1778421427493,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How do we handle Latency ?\n\n- In our process, the operation that takes more time would be the database lookups.\n- Soltuion to make the queries & lookups more efficient:\n \n   1. Indexing\n     - Each table we can have some Primary key [ Ensures Uniquness & Index is created on that column/key]\n     - This index is kept in memory not always tho. i.e a pointer to the main row in the table.\n     - Incase of \"Postgress\" -> Indexing is implemented using Btree.\n        -> It is a self balancing tree.\n        -> the lookup time complexity would be O(log n).\n   \n    Optional:   \n        We can additonally create a 2nd index on shortUrl key: HashIndex.\n        - The lookup will be O(1).\n        -  This is optional ofcourse ! In Postgress this lookups using BTree are very well optimised. for equals checks. \n\n    2. Add a cache [ Redis ]\n        - we are going to use it's RAM for fast access. - read Thorugh. LRU ( Least Recently used ) cache.\n        - Flow:\n          Anytime we need the long url for the short url -> look in the cache first -> If missed -> then look in database.\n          update the cache and return the result.\n          LRU here is the evicting policy, where we clean those cached results which are least used.\n\n   3. Also we can cache the url in a CDN:\n        - CDN is Content Delivery Network, these are small servers which are geographically located around the world.\n        - This best way for fast delivering resukt if the primary server and the user ares countries apart.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How do we handle Latency ?\n\n- In our process, the operation that takes more time would be the database lookups.\n- Soltuion to make the queries & lookups more efficient:\n \n   1. Indexing\n     - Each table we can have some Primary key [ Ensures Uniquness & Index is created on that column/key]\n     - This index is kept in memory not always tho. i.e a pointer to the main row in the table.\n     - Incase of \"Postgress\" -> Indexing is implemented using Btree.\n        -> It is a self balancing tree.\n        -> the lookup time complexity would be O(log n).\n   \n    Optional:   \n        We can additonally create a 2nd index on shortUrl key: HashIndex.\n        - The lookup will be O(1).\n        -  This is optional ofcourse ! In Postgress this lookups using BTree are very well optimised. for equals checks. \n\n    2. Add a cache [ Redis ]\n        - we are going to use it's RAM for fast access. - read Thorugh. LRU ( Least Recently used ) cache.\n        - Flow:\n          Anytime we need the long url for the short url -> look in the cache first -> If missed -> then look in database.\n          update the cache and return the result.\n          LRU here is the evicting policy, where we clean those cached results which are least used.\n\n   3. Also we can cache the url in a CDN:\n        - CDN is Content Delivery Network, these are small servers which are geographically located around the world.\n        - This best way for fast delivering resukt if the primary server and the user ares countries apart.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
