    },
    {
      "id": "POwI4GhIxtL0miSwUF5jg",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2535.7896213924514,
      "y": 2089.4691020279997,
      "width": 1238.339111328125,
      "height": 1050,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b02",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1723530478,
      "version": 2809,
      "versionNonce": 1678409006,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1778421424309,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Addressing the Scaling problem:\n\nWe go from left to right while addressing scalings in out system design.\n\n- How many reqs does the primary server gets hit ?\n\n    100M or 10^8 users -> Let's assume they all make avg 1 - 2 url redirects in a day.\n    ~ 10^5 seconds in a day...\n\n    10^8 requests / 10^ 5 secs -> 10^3 or 1000 rps [ Requests per second ] on daily basis..\n\n    - Peak consideration: lets assume (x10) for safe side: 1000 * 10  = 10^4 rps @ peak max. i.e Range [10k - 100k rps]\n    \n    - A EC2 avg instance can handle around 1000 rps [ depends on requests, bandwidth, CPU & memory ]\n\nSolution:\n    Option 1: Vertically Scaling\n        - Make the server box biggerr --> Go to a bigger machine with more CPU, more Processing power, handle more bandwidth.\n        - It is more expensive.\n    \n    Option 2: Horizontally Scalling [ More Common appraoch in System design ]\n        - We have more of this boxes and we distribute the traffic among these boxes.\n        - This is what we will consider in our problem statement.\n        - Problem:\n          There are lot of reads in our system, the create urls will be hit <<< reading the long url from short url.\n           So, the create short url doesn't need to scale but the read short urls must scale.\n          \n    Solution:\n        - We can move to a micro service Architecture. A Read Service &  A Write Service both can scale independently.\n        - To re-direct the reqs to these microserve, we need a new component: API Gateway.\n        - Now we can scale the Read Service, have a lot of them !!\n        \n        Problem:\n           - It;s a good approach, but a bit of an over kill !!! \n           - The read and write service, have very little code in it --> So to seperate them out doesnot quiet make sense.\n           - Probably should keep in same box and scale them...\n             \n    The Scaling of these instances on modern cloud deployed env is Automatically handled by the Cloud servive Probiders. \n    So the these AWS instances and google cloud, we can set the CPU and RAM limts.\n    - So we say, if 75% of the memory or CPU is used, throw up a new  box !! If 25% of the less is used, kick existing box ! \n\n    Auto SCaling Baby !!!",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Addressing the Scaling problem:\n\nWe go from left to right while addressing scalings in out system design.\n\n- How many reqs does the primary server gets hit ?\n\n    100M or 10^8 users -> Let's assume they all make avg 1 - 2 url redirects in a day.\n    ~ 10^5 seconds in a day...\n\n    10^8 requests / 10^ 5 secs -> 10^3 or 1000 rps [ Requests per second ] on daily basis..\n\n    - Peak consideration: lets assume (x10) for safe side: 1000 * 10  = 10^4 rps @ peak max. i.e Range [10k - 100k rps]\n    \n    - A EC2 avg instance can handle around 1000 rps [ depends on requests, bandwidth, CPU & memory ]\n\nSolution:\n    Option 1: Vertically Scaling\n        - Make the server box biggerr --> Go to a bigger machine with more CPU, more Processing power, handle more bandwidth.\n        - It is more expensive.\n    \n    Option 2: Horizontally Scalling [ More Common appraoch in System design ]\n        - We have more of this boxes and we distribute the traffic among these boxes.\n        - This is what we will consider in our problem statement.\n        - Problem:\n          There are lot of reads in our system, the create urls will be hit <<< reading the long url from short url.\n           So, the create short url doesn't need to scale but the read short urls must scale.\n          \n    Solution:\n        - We can move to a micro service Architecture. A Read Service &  A Write Service both can scale independently.\n        - To re-direct the reqs to these microserve, we need a new component: API Gateway.\n        - Now we can scale the Read Service, have a lot of them !!\n        \n        Problem:\n           - It;s a good approach, but a bit of an over kill !!! \n           - The read and write service, have very little code in it --> So to seperate them out doesnot quiet make sense.\n           - Probably should keep in same box and scale them...\n             \n    The Scaling of these instances on modern cloud deployed env is Automatically handled by the Cloud servive Probiders. \n    So the these AWS instances and google cloud, we can set the CPU and RAM limts.\n    - So we say, if 75% of the memory or CPU is used, throw up a new  box !! If 25% of the less is used, kick existing box ! \n\n    Auto SCaling Baby !!!",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "W_uMjypXggnvcGwDKmJ59",
      "type": "rectangle",
      "x": 971.2430881052792,
      "y": 1672.9321664322574,
      "width": 334.5562961158354,
      "height": 218.72651629515187,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
