    },
    {
      "id": "zUywmqCGg_BvizR9CAqfT",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2583.067720298251,
      "y": 3258.2204095495404,
      "width": 1200.6793212890625,
      "height": 475,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b05",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1961877486,
      "version": 1207,
      "versionNonce": 755486062,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1778421433627,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Issue with Write Service  Because of Scaling\n\nWE do have a counter for uniqueness of the shorturls -> But if we have multiple instances of the same service. \nthen how to manage this ?\n\nSolution:\nPull the Counter out of the services and point towards a global counter. -> It counld be Redis.\n-> The Write service instances now going to ask the Global Counter for what is the next Count should be ?\n-> Redis:\n    We have \"INCR\" a command that increment the counter in memory !\n     -> It is single threaded -> so no concurrency issue ! -> It is Lightining fast too !!  \n\nA Catch here:\nWE added an additional step of requesting for the count and then process it. -> A REST call will go, some additional job !\nThis can be solved like:\n When the servers comes on-line -> request the Global counter for next 1000 counters -> Kept in server internal memory.\n IF server crash -> those 1000 counts lost -> but that's okay ! No big deal !\n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Issue with Write Service  Because of Scaling\n\nWE do have a counter for uniqueness of the shorturls -> But if we have multiple instances of the same service. \nthen how to manage this ?\n\nSolution:\nPull the Counter out of the services and point towards a global counter. -> It counld be Redis.\n-> The Write service instances now going to ask the Global Counter for what is the next Count should be ?\n-> Redis:\n    We have \"INCR\" a command that increment the counter in memory !\n     -> It is single threaded -> so no concurrency issue ! -> It is Lightining fast too !!  \n\nA Catch here:\nWE added an additional step of requesting for the count and then process it. -> A REST call will go, some additional job !\nThis can be solved like:\n When the servers comes on-line -> request the Global counter for next 1000 counters -> Kept in server internal memory.\n IF server crash -> those 1000 counts lost -> but that's okay ! No big deal !\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "rgxPhe6Y7FGNf9-MY2sd2",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1638.1178964388828,
      "y": 1956.0175593222064,
      "width": 614.279541015625,
      "height": 350,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b06",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2021350510,
      "version": 999,
      "versionNonce": 988498542,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1778421484226,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Scaling of the database\n\n- Per Rows in database lets say ~500 bytes for characters \n                                                 and short url texts.\n  So we store 1B urls.\n    ~ 500 bytes * 1 B = 500 GB  [ Managable ]\n\nModern SSDs are in scale of 100s of TeraBytes.\n\n- Can our database handles the read-through put ?\n  Most of our reads are handled in the cache !\n\n- Even if we want to scale the database -> shard it based on \nthe shorturl -> Multiple instane of database !",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Scaling of the database\n\n- Per Rows in database lets say ~500 bytes for characters \n                                                 and short url texts.\n  So we store 1B urls.\n    ~ 500 bytes * 1 B = 500 GB  [ Managable ]\n\nModern SSDs are in scale of 100s of TeraBytes.\n\n- Can our database handles the read-through put ?\n  Most of our reads are handled in the cache !\n\n- Even if we want to scale the database -> shard it based on \nthe shorturl -> Multiple instane of database !",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
